  "signature": "ed25519:7b3e1a9f4c2d8e6b0f5a3c7d9e2b4f1a6c8d0e3f5b7a9c1d4e6f8a2b0c3d5e7f",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) operates under a validated quality management system conforming to 21 CFR Part 820 and ISO 13485. Version control, change management, and regression testing protocols documented in the software QMS dossier. Required Gradation 2 mandates documented QMS with periodic audits.",
      "rationale": "The simulation software suite is maintained under an ISO 13485-certified QMS. Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is used under a controlled installation with documented version locking. Internal regression tests are executed quarterly and results archived in the quality management system. The achieved level exceeds the required level for this Medium model risk context."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification benchmarks must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations for contact mechanics and large-deformation elastoplasticity. Required Gradation 2 mandates at least one published benchmark with documented pass/fail criteria. Achieved Gradation 3 includes two independent benchmark suites with quantitative error metrics.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical code verification was demonstrated against the NAFEMS benchmark suite (LE1, LE10, NL2) and the ASME V&V 10.1 benchmark problems. All benchmark deviations were below 0.5% relative error. Contact formulation was verified against the Hertzian contact analytical solution. Results are archived in the project verification report VR-2023-001."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence must be demonstrated via a systematic refinement study with at least three mesh densities. The discretization error in each QoI must be quantified and shown to be less than 5% of the QoI value at the reported mesh density. Required Gradation 3 mandates Richardson extrapolation or equivalent formal error estimation.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the screw-rod construct model. Element edge lengths of 1.0 mm, 0.5 mm, and 0.25 mm were evaluated. Richardson extrapolation yielded discretization errors of 1.8%, 2.3%, and 1.1% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm respectively at the production mesh density (0.5 mm). All values are below the 5% acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver convergence must be verified by demonstrating that residual norms fall below 1e-4 for each load step and that energy balance is satisfied within 0.1%. Required Gradation 2 mandates documented convergence monitoring for all production runs.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver convergence was monitored using force residual and displacement residual norms. All load steps converged to residuals below 1e-5. Energy balance was confirmed within 0.05% across all 11 simulation instances. Convergence logs are archived in the simulation record database SR-2023-F1717."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Use error controls must include documented simulation execution procedures, independent review of model setup, and traceability of all analyst decisions to a simulation plan. Required Gradation 2 mandates a documented simulation plan reviewed by a second analyst.",
      "rationale": "A detailed simulation execution plan (SEP-2023-001) was authored by the primary analyst and independently reviewed by a senior simulation engineer. All boundary condition assignments, material property selections, and contact definitions were cross-checked against the SEP prior to execution. Analyst decisions are traceable to the SEP via electronic signatures in the PLM system."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form adequacy must be justified by demonstrating that the chosen constitutive models, contact formulations, and geometric representations are appropriate for the COU physics. Required Gradation 3 mandates literature-supported justification for each major modeling assumption with sensitivity analysis for at least one assumption.",
      "rationale": "The bilinear isotropic hardening model for Ti-6Al-4V was selected based on published material characterization data (Donachie 2000, Reilly & Burstein 1975). Frictional contact (μ=0.2) at the screw-rod interface was justified by tribological literature for dry titanium-titanium contact. A sensitivity study on friction coefficient (μ=0.1 to 0.3) showed less than 3% variation in all QoIs. Geometric fidelity was confirmed by comparing CAD dimensions to coordinate measurement machine data."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs must be traceable to primary sources (material certificates or published characterization studies). Uncertainty in key inputs must be quantified and propagated to QoI uncertainty. Required Gradation 3 mandates documented uncertainty quantification for at least the two most influential input parameters.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) were taken from lot-specific material certificates for the production screw stock. Geometric dimensions were obtained from the validated CAD model with tolerances from the device drawing. Uncertainty propagation via Monte Carlo sampling (N=1000) across elastic modulus ±5% and yield strength ±3% yielded QoI uncertainty bands of ±4.1% for stiffness and ±3.8% for yield force."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples must be representative of the production device population. Sample size must be sufficient to characterize inter-specimen variability. Required Gradation 3 mandates N≥10 specimens with documented traceability to production lot and dimensional inspection of each specimen.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production-representative hardware (Lot 2022-NC-7.5). Each construct underwent dimensional inspection confirming conformance to drawing tolerances. Specimens were distributed across two independent test laboratories (Lab A: N=6, Lab B: N=5) to assess inter-laboratory variability. Sample size satisfies the N≥10 requirement for Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of conditions relevant to the COU. Required Gradation 3 mandates testing under at least two distinct loading configurations or environmental conditions representative of the COU envelope. Achieved Gradation 2 reflects that only a single load configuration (ASTM F1717 standard compression-bending at 5° offset) was evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted exclusively under the ASTM F1717 standard compression-bending configuration at a 5-degree caudal offset angle, which is the regulatory standard for this device class. While the COU encompasses the full range of in vivo loading conditions, the F1717 protocol represents the most demanding standardized configuration and is accepted by FDA as the primary validation benchmark for pedicle screw constructs. The limitation to a single test condition is acknowledged; however, the model form validation (factor: Model form) and sensitivity analyses partially compensate by demonstrating low sensitivity to boundary condition perturbations. This factor is rated below the required level and is identified as a gap in the credibility argument."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The equivalency of simulation input parameters to experimental conditions was established through a systematic mapping exercise documented in the Validation Plan VP-2023-F1717. Fixture geometry, load application point, support span (100 mm), and crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min quasi-static) were replicated identically in the FEA boundary conditions. Material properties used in the model were drawn from the same production lot as the test specimens. Torque applied to set screws (4 Nm per manufacturer IFU) was represented in the model via pre-tension elements with equivalent bolt-load boundary conditions. The inter-laboratory setup variability was quantified by comparing fixture compliance between Lab A and Lab B; the difference was 1.2 N/mm (2.4% of mean construct stiffness) and was incorporated into the validation uncertainty budget. Independent dimensional verification confirmed that screw geometry in the CAD model matched the as-manufactured specimens to within 0.03 mm across all critical features. The mapping was reviewed and approved by both the primary analyst and the independent validation engineer prior to any simulation execution, ensuring that no post-hoc parameter adjustments were made to improve agreement. This systematic equivalency documentation satisfies Gradation 3 requirements for this factor under the ASME V&V 40-2018 framework and provides the evidentiary basis for treating the experimental dataset as a valid comparator for the FEA predictions across all three quantities of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative output comparison must use a validation metric that accounts for both model prediction error and experimental uncertainty. Required Gradation 3 mandates use of a normalized validation metric (e.g., E/uval) with a pre-specified acceptance threshold applied to all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "The ASME V&V 10.1 validation metric E/uval was computed for all three QoIs. Stiffness: E/uval = 0.82 (threshold <1.96). Yield force: E/uval = 1.14 (threshold <1.96). Force at 40 mm: E/uval = 0.67 (threshold <1.96). All metrics satisfy the pre-specified acceptance threshold. Percentage differences were 4.1%, 6.8%, and 3.2% respectively, all below the 10% QoI difference bound. Comparison plots with experimental mean ± 2SD bands are provided in Appendix C of the validation report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must be demonstrably linked to the clinical performance endpoints and regulatory submission requirements. Required Gradation 3 mandates documented traceability from each QoI to a specific clinical or regulatory requirement with justification for the chosen metric.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in the FDA guidance document for spinal implant testing. Each QoI is traceable to the device design requirement specification (DRS-2022-001, Requirements R-14, R-15, R-16). Clinical relevance is established by the association between construct stiffness and fusion rate outcomes in the published literature (Slosar et al. 2000, Glassman et al. 1992)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation activities must be shown to be relevant to the COU by demonstrating that the validation domain encompasses the COU domain for the critical QoIs. Required Gradation 3 mandates a documented relevance argument with explicit identification of any gaps between the validation domain and COU domain.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities directly replicate the regulatory test standard (ASTM F1717) that defines the primary performance envelope for this device class. The COU is to support a 510(k) submission using FEA predictions of F1717 performance; the validation activities are therefore directly co-extensive with the COU domain. The single identified gap — testing at only one load configuration — is addressed in the Test conditions factor and noted as a residual limitation in the overall credibility argument. No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is claimed."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The overall credibility assessment is Accepted at Medium assurance level. Twelve of thirteen credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single below-level factor (Test conditions, achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) is acknowledged and accepted on the basis that ASTM F1717 is the regulatory standard for this device class, FDA guidance does not require multi-condition testing for 510(k) submissions of this type, and the model form sensitivity analyses demonstrate low sensitivity to boundary condition perturbations. The validation metric E/uval is below 1.96 for all three QoIs, and percentage differences are below 10% for all QoIs. The credibility evidence is sufficient to support the intended regulatory use.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
